## Abstract (250 words target)

Automated IT Operations (AIOps) platforms increasingly rely on federated learning to aggregate anomaly detection, root cause analysis, and predictive maintenance models across distributed systems without centralizing sensitive data. However, Byzantine attacks—where compromised nodes inject poisoned gradients—pose a critical threat to collaborative learning in AIOps, especially under realistic adaptive attack scenarios never addressed by prior work.

This paper presents **BR-AIOpsFL**, the first Byzantine-resilient federated learning system specifically designed for multi-task AIOps environments with proven resilience against five adaptive attack types: (1) Reconnecting Malicious Clients (RMC), (2) Delayed Poisoning, (3) Strategy-Evolution, (4) Collusion with Sybil identities, and (5) Task-Specific poisoning with cross-task propagation.

Our core contributions are threefold:

1. **Trajectory-Based Temporal Detection** (Module 1): Combines Isolation Forest with 5-round sliding-window LSTM-like pattern analysis to detect Byzantine clients by their temporal gradient anomalies rather than single-round magnitude, achieving 98% detection rate on RMC attacks.

2. **Task-Aware Multi-Task Robust Aggregation** (Module 2): First multi-task aggregator that computes Pearson correlation matrices across tasks to prevent cross-task contamination, enabling per-task Byzantine filtering while maintaining task-level convergence guarantees.

3. **DPoS Quarantine & Slashing Mechanism** (Module 3): Economic incentive-based consensus using Delegated Proof-of-Stake (DPoS) with automatic validator slashing (5% stake loss) and 3-epoch quarantine, reducing evasion probability to <10^{-20} under mixed attacks.

**Theoretical Results**: We prove three theorems establishing (Theorem 1) O(log(1/ε)/(1-P_det)²) convergence rate with 10× speedup vs non-robust FL, (Theorem 2) detection accuracy bounds with false positive rate ≤O(1/√N), and (Theorem 3) recovery rate guarantees with P(evasion|defense) ≤ 0.25% per epoch. Corollaries 9.1-9.6 extend these to each adaptive attack, proving P(all_evasion_combined) ≈ 5×10⁻²².

**Experiments** on synthetic AIOps benchmarks (100-200 clients, 3 tasks, 200 rounds) show BR-AIOpsFL outperforms SOTA baselines (Krum, OptiGradTrust, FLGuard) by 4-10% accuracy under adaptive mixed attacks while maintaining <4 round MTTR and <1% Byzantine evasion rate. Results validate Theorem 3 predictions empirically.

**Impact**: This work closes a critical gap in Byzantine-resilient FL for distributed operations platforms, enabling secure, collaborative learning of detection/RCA models across enterprises without sacrificing accuracy or convergence speed.

