## 3. System Model & Threat Model

### 3.1 Federated Learning Setup

[~250 words]

**Participants**:
- N clients (monitoring agents, edge nodes, branch offices) indexed i ∈ [N]
- 1 trusted aggregator (central coordinator)
- M federated tasks indexed j ∈ [M] (anomaly detection, RCA, forecasting)

**Data & Model**:
- Client i holds local dataset D_i (metrics from site i)
- Task j has model parameters w^j ∈ ℝ^d (shared globally)
- Per-round client i computes gradient ∇L_i^j(w^j) via SGD on D_i
- Aggregator averages gradients: w^j ← w^j - η Σ_i ∇L_i^j(w^j) / N

**Multi-Task Learning**: Shared encoder layer + task-specific heads. Cross-task gradient mixing enabled via shared representation (realistic AIOps: shared feature extraction from common metrics like CPU/memory/latency).

**Threat Model**:
- Up to B ≤ 0.4N clients are Byzantine (compromised)
- Byzantine clients can:
  - Observe current global model w^j (synchronous FL)
  - Submit arbitrary gradients g_i^j (not necessarily from SGD)
  - Coordinate with other Byzantine clients (no limit on communication among Byzantine nodes)
  - Spawn Sybil identities (fake client IDs)
- Honest clients compute gradients correctly but may be compromised after training (restart with old model possible → RMC attack)

### 3.2 AIOps Metrics & Success Criteria

[~150 words]

**Operational Goals**:
1. Model accuracy >92% (baseline AIOps SLA)
2. MTTR <30 minutes (industry standard; in rounds: ~5-10 rounds @ 1 round/min)
3. Alert precision >85% (reduce false positives / alert fatigue)
4. RCA success rate >90% (correct root cause identified)

**Security Goals**:
1. Byzantine detection F1 >0.90
2. Evasion rate <5% (% Byzantine clients escaping detection)
3. No convergence poisoning (final model utility maintained)

